ESP32-C3 WiFi Weather Station connected to Home Assistant via MQTT:

WiFi-connected weather station built with an ESP32-C3, featuring a DHT11 sensor, an I2C OLED display, and full Home Assistant integration via MQTT.

Features
  Auto Screen Rotation: Cycles every 5 seconds between:

  Indoor Stats: Real-time temperature and humidity, WiFi/MQTT connection status, and the last octet of the device IP address.

  Outdoor Stats: Real-time weather data pulled via API from the National Weather Service (KSAT Station).

  Forecast and Sun: Current sky conditions and localized Sunrise/Sunset times.

  Home Assistant Ready: Automatic MQTT discovery for seamless dashboard integration without manual YAML configuration.

  OTA (Over-the-Air) Updates: Wireless firmware flashing capabilities using the ArduinoOTA library.

  Auto-Dimming: Built-in support for display dimming via MQTT commands from Home Assistant.

Hardware Used
  Microcontroller: ESP32-C3 (SuperMini or DevKit)

  Sensor: DHT11 (Temperature & Humidity)

  Display: 0.96 inch SSD1306 I2C OLED (128x64)

  Power: USB-C or 5V DC input

Software and Libraries
  Environment: Built using PlatformIO and C++

  Display: Adafruit_SSD1306 and Adafruit_GFX

  Sensor: DHT sensor library and Adafruit Unified Sensor

  Networking: PubSubClient (MQTT), HTTPClient, and ArduinoOTA

  Data Parsing: ArduinoJson (v7.0+)

Home Assistant Integration
  Discovery: The device automatically appears in Home Assistant under the MQTT integration as "C3 Temp" and "C3 Hum".

  Reporting: Sensor data is published to the state topic every 30 seconds.

  Controls: The display brightness can be toggled via the configured dim_topic.